ught to move them to action. Blood of Others presents these works as vivid evidence of literature’s power to lift our moral horizons. In bringing these remarkable texts to light and contextualizing them among Russian, Turkish, and Ukrainian representations of Crimea from 1783, Rory Finnin provides an innovative cultural history of the Black Sea region. He reveals how a "poetics of solidarity" promoted empathy and support for oppressed people through complex provocations of guilt rather than shame. Forging new roads between Slavic studies and Middle Eastern studies, Blood of Others is a compelling and timely exploration of the ideas and identities coursing between Russia, Turkey, and Ukraine – three countries determining the fate of a volatile and geopolitically pivotal part of our world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEthnic relations in literature. 0aLiterature and societyzUkrainezCrimeaxHistoryy20th century. 0aTatarszUkrainezCrimeaxHistoryy20th century. 0aTatarszUkrainezCrimeaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aUkrainian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Eastern (see also Russian & Former Soviet Union).2bisacsh  aBlack Sea region.  aCrimea.  aCrimean Tatars.  aRepublic of Turkey.  aRussian literary history.  aSlavic literature.  aSoviet Russia.  aStalin.  aUkraine.  acomparative literature.  aliterature.  apoetics of solidarity.  asolidarity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076715540uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753700540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487537005423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487537005/original  a978-3-11-076715-5  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL